From
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH307/December_2012/Question_04_(b)}{part
(b)} we have the formula $c_n=\int_{0}^{1}f(t)e^{-2\pi int}\,dt.$
Plugging in \emph{n = 0} we calculate

\begin{align*}
c_0 &= \int_{0}^{1}f(t)e^{-2\pi i(0)t}\,dt \\
&= \int_{0}^{1}(t^2-t)(1)dt \\
&=\frac{1}{3}-\frac{1}{2}=-\frac{1}{6}
\end{align*}
